# Git Workflow — Cursor Rules

## CRITICAL: Branch Discipline

You MUST follow these rules for EVERY task that modifies files:

### Before starting ANY work
1. Check current branch: `git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD`
2. If on `main`, you MUST create a feature branch first:
   ```bash
   ./scripts/git_workflow.sh start feat <slug>   # for features
   ./scripts/git_workflow.sh start fix <slug>     # for bug fixes
   ```
3. NEVER commit directly to `main`. This is a hard rule with no exceptions.
4. Branch slugs must be lowercase-hyphenated: `fix-filament-dropdown`, `feat-ams-slot-cards`

### Choosing feat vs fix
- `fix/` — Corrects broken behavior, resolves bugs, patches issues
- `feat/` — Adds new functionality, new views, new automations, new sensors

### During work
- Use `./scripts/git_workflow.sh commit "message"` instead of raw `git commit`
  - This runs pre-commit gates automatically (serious_mode_check.sh, etc.)
  - It stages all changes and adds the `Made-with: Cursor` trailer
- Check status anytime: `./scripts/git_workflow.sh status`
- If main has advanced, rebase: `./scripts/git_workflow.sh sync`

### Commit message format
Write clear, descriptive commit messages:
- First line: imperative mood, under 72 chars (e.g. "Fix filament dropdown not populating after restart")
- If multiple logical changes, make multiple commits — one per logical unit
- Reference the problem being solved, not just what was done

### When work is complete
Run the full finish pipeline:
```bash
./scripts/git_workflow.sh finish "PR Title: Description of changes"
```

This will:
1. Stage and commit any pending changes
2. Run ALL gates (serious_mode_check, skill_test, validate_helpers)
3. Push to origin
4. Create a GitHub PR via `gh` CLI

If any gate fails, FIX the issue and re-run `finish`. Do NOT skip gates.

### If you need to abandon work
```bash
./scripts/git_workflow.sh abort
```
This discards changes and deletes the local branch.

## Gate Reference

### Pre-commit gates (run before every commit)
- `./scripts/serious_mode_check.sh` — YAML lint, formatting checks
- Must be on a feature branch (not main)
- Must have staged changes

### Pre-merge gates (run before PR creation)
- `./scripts/skill_test.sh` — Full HA integration test suite
- `./scripts/validate_helpers.sh` — All 60+ input helpers healthy and reachable
- All pre-commit gates must also pass

## Deployment Integration

### Stage deployment (for testing)
After committing on your feature branch:
```bash
./scripts/manage_ha.sh --config    # if configuration.yaml changed
./scripts/manage_ha.sh --restart   # if configuration.yaml changed
./scripts/manage_ha.sh --stage     # deploy dashboard to stage
./scripts/manage_ha.sh --automations  # reload automations if changed
```

### The finish command does NOT deploy
Deployment to stage is a manual step during development. The `finish` command only runs gates, pushes, and creates a PR. You should deploy and test on stage BEFORE running finish.

### Prod deployment
Prod deployment happens AFTER the PR is merged to main. It is a separate manual process (copy dashboard YAML to storage dashboard, restart HA, etc.).

## Workflow Summary

```
1. ./scripts/git_workflow.sh start feat/fix <slug>
2. Make changes
3. ./scripts/git_workflow.sh commit "description"
4. Deploy to stage and test manually
5. Repeat 2-4 as needed
6. ./scripts/git_workflow.sh finish "PR title"
7. Jerry reviews PR in GitHub
8. Squash-merge to main
```

## What NOT to do
- ❌ `git commit` directly (use `git_workflow.sh commit`)
- ❌ `git checkout main && git commit` (never commit to main)
- ❌ `git push origin main` (never push to main directly)
- ❌ Skip gates because "it's a small change"
- ❌ Work on multiple feature branches simultaneously in one session
- ❌ Merge branches locally (PRs are merged in GitHub)
